<DOC><DOCNO> AP890727-0234 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0235EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-27 0876</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0914</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Congressional negotiators agreed to limitsavings and loans' investment in junk bonds and pledged keepworking to resolve other differences holding up themultibillion-dollar Sandamp;L bailout.   A compromise adopted Wednesday by representatives of the Houseand Senate would require Sandamp;Ls to sell their high-risk, high-yieldbonds as soon as possible but no later than Aug. 1, 1994.   The offer does not address the biggest issue dividing the Houseand Senate _ whether Sandamp;L spending is included in the budgetdeficit. The Bush administration and the Senate want to keep it out.</TEXT><DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anti-union workers predicted a decisivevictory as assembly-line workers who once embraced Japanese-styleteam management voted whether to unionize a Nissan auto plant.   The United Auto Workers, seeking to organize 2,400 hourlyemployees at Nissan Motor Manufacturing U.S.A., also forecastsuccess in Wednesday's vote. Workers who once sang the praises ofNissan management have charged that the plant is run at a breakneckspeed that has resulted in a high rate of injury. Nissan has warnedthat a union could jeopardize benefits and plant unity and that theautomaker will be a tough bargainer if the union wins.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Labor experts said the autoworkers voting inTennessee were deciding not only whether the United Auto Workersunion would represent them, but also the course of the union'sbroader future.   The vote Wednesday at Nissan Motor Corp.'s car and truckassembly plant in Smyrna, Tenn., was viewed as critical for theunion, which was attempting to organize a plant in a right-to-workstate.   It also may foreshadow the results of the drive by the UAW _which has seen membership shrink by 33 percent in the last 10 years_ to organize the widespread, mostly unorganized automobilesupplier industry.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Digital audio tape players, which combinecompact disc-quality sound with recordability, could be in storesby Christmas under an accord set to be announced Thursday.   Under the agreement, all DAT players sold in the United Stateswill contain a chip that limits copying of digital tapes. Recordcompanies insisted on the copy protection for fear that widespreadcopying would cut into their sales of compact discs.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Visa and MasterCard conspired to prevent othercompanies from introducing a national debit card network whiledelaying the launch of a debit card they created jointly, 12 statesclaim in a lawsuit.   A debit card can be presented at stores like a credit card, butthe money is automatically transferred from the card-holder'saccount to the merchant's.   ``You don't have to be an expert in antitrust law. It's the mostbasic common sense to see what they're up to,'' New York AttorneyGeneral Robert Abrams said Wednesday at a news conference after thecivil lawsuit was filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Cornell University graduate student wasindicted on a felony charge stemming from creation of a roguecomputer ``virus'' that paralyzed as many as 6,000 computers lastfall.   Robert Tappan Morris, 24, who has been suspended from theuniversity for one year, was indicted Wednesday by a federal grandjury in Syracuse, N.Y., on a single count of accessing withoutauthorization at least six university and military computers.   The Justice Department said Morris was the first person to becharged under the computer-crime provision of the Computer Fraudand Abuse Act of 1986.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher defendedthe Bush administration against congressional criticism thatconsumers could be hurt by the administration's efforts to modifyantitrust laws.   Mosbacher said Wednesday the administration would ``very soon''present Congress with its recommendations for relaxing antitrustlaws, so companies can jointly produce high-technology products,such as high-definition television sets.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush ended the nation's last pricecontrols on natural gas and announced his administration willtravel the country soliciting suggestions for an energy policykeyed to market forces.   The bill Bush signed Wednesday ends the last wellhead pricecontrols on natural gas, 35 years after they were begun.   The law removes controls on the remaining one-third of naturalgas supplies subject to price ceilings. The ceilings will beabolished by January 1993 for existing wells and by May 1991 forwells drilled from now on.</TEXT><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   SmithKline Beecham, a new internationalpharmaceutical firm, was created after SmithKline Beckman Corp.shareholders overwhelmingly approved a merger with Beecham GroupPLC of Britain.   With combined sales exceeding $6 billion, SmithKline Beechambecomes the world's second-largest pharmaceutical company afterMerck andamp; Co.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A late buying wave buoyed blue chip stocks, carrying the DowJones industrial average back above the 2,600-mark as the marketmoved broadly higher Wednesday. The average of 30 industrialssurged by 29.97 to a new post-crash high of 2,613.05.   The dollar sank in response to more signs that the FederalReserve was loosening credit.   Bond prices finished little changed in quiet trading.   Crude oil futures prices slipped to a 5{-month low on the NewYork Mercantile Exchange, while on other markets, precious metalsadvanced, grains and soybeans were mixed and livestock and meatfutures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>